<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 7:14<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If5cf2ad16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I358217d0933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>7.</label.designator><headtext>Selection of a Transferee Judge</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94f968e6e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>7:14.</label.designator><headtext>Assignment of multiple judges</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel can assign a docket to multiple judge. <eos/><bos/>It has done so in a complex set of cases involving claims against various mutual funds in a single “family” of funds.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If5cf51e06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] The Panel determined to transfer a wide variety of actions in a single centralized docket rather than transferring cases fund by fund. <eos/><bos/>In transferring to multiple judges in a single district, the Panel empowered each judge to act individually or jointly.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If5cf51e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In the cases arising from the terrorist attacks on the United States on September 11, 2001, the Panel noted the possibility of assigning a judge from the District of District of Columbia to deal with proceedings there, both because one of the hijacked planes was crashed into the Pentagon and because of the likelihood of federal governmental involvement in the litigation, but decided against doing so.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If5cf51e26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If5cf2ad16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If5cf51e06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914098" w-serial-number="2004168728" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0004637" ID="I6482f8416b3e11e984eaf7fbfa3d7525">In re Janus Mut. Funds Inv. Litigation, 310 F. Supp. 2d 1359 (J.P.M.L. 2004)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If5cf51e16b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914098" w-serial-number="2004168728" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0004637" w-pinpoint-page="1362" ID="I64836d716b3e11e984eaf7fbfa3d7525">310 F. Supp. 2d at 1362</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If5cf51e26b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304914098" w-serial-number="2003923589" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0004637" ID="I648409b16b3e11e984eaf7fbfa3d7525">In re Terrorist Attacks on September 11, 2001, 295 F. Supp. 2d 1377 (J.P.M.L. 2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 7:14<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
